TITLE: Sending Transactions via Privy Embedded Wallet (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: These TypeScript snippets demonstrate how to send a transaction using the user's Privy embedded wallet. The `useSendTransaction` hook provides the `sendTransaction` function. A button triggers the custom `transfer` function. The `transfer` function first checks if the user is authenticated and the address is available. It then constructs a transaction object specifying the value (`ethers.parseUnits` converts ECH amount to Wei), destination address (`to`), and sender address (`from`, which is the user's embedded wallet address). Calling `sendTransaction` with this object prompts the user with a Privy modal to review and approve the transaction.
SOURCE: https://github.com/ava-labs/builders-hub.git/blob/master/content/guides/use-privy-on-l1.mdx#2025-04-23_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { useSendTransaction } from '@privy-io/react-auth';
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
<button onClick={transfer}>Send Test Transfer via Privy</button>
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { useSendTransaction, usePrivy } from '@privy-io/react-auth';
import { ethers } from 'ethers';

// Inside your React component
const { authenticated, user } = usePrivy(); // Get user object for wallet address
const { sendTransaction } = useSendTransaction();
const address = user?.wallet?.address; // Get embedded wallet address

const transfer = () => {
    if (authenticated === false || address === undefined) {
        console.log('User not authenticated or address not found');
        return;
    }
    let receiver = "0x..."; // Replace with a valid receiver address
    const tx = {
        value: ethers.parseUnits("0.01", "ether"),
        to: receiver as `0x${string}`,
        from: address as `0x${string}`, // logged in user's embedded wallet address
        // No 'chainId' or 'gas' needed, Privy handles this
    };

    console.log('Attempting to send transaction:', tx);

    sendTransaction(tx).then(receipt => {
        console.log('Transaction successful:', receipt);
    }).catch((err) => {
        console.error('Transaction failed:', err);
        // handle err (e.g., show error message to user)
    });
}
```

