TITLE: Displaying User Info and Fetching Balance with Viem (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: These TypeScript snippets show how to display user information after login and fetch their wallet balance. The first snippet (JSX) accesses the `user` object from Privy (likely via `usePrivy`) to display the user's Privy ID (`user.id`) and embedded wallet address (`user.wallet.address`). The second snippet sets up a Viem `createPublicClient` configured for the custom `echo` chain and uses its `getBalance` method to fetch the native token balance for the user's address. The balance (returned as a BigInt) is then formatted into a readable string using `ethers.formatEther` and stored in component state (`setBalance`).
SOURCE: https://github.com/ava-labs/builders-hub.git/blob/master/content/guides/use-privy-on-l1.mdx#2025-04-23_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
// Assuming 'user' object is available from usePrivy() hook
// Assuming 'balance' state variable exists
<span>{user.id}</span>
<span>{user.wallet.address}</span>
<span>{balance} ECH</span>
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { createPublicClient, http } from 'viem';
import { ethers } from 'ethers';
import { echo } from './chains'; // Assuming echo is defined in './chains.ts'
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

// Inside your React component, assuming 'address' is the user's wallet address
const [balance, setBalance] = useState<string>('0');

useEffect(() => {
  if (address) {
    const client = createPublicClient({
        chain: echo,
        transport: http(),
    });
    // get native asset balance
    client.getBalance({
        address: address as `0x${string}`, // Cast address to Viem's expected Address type
    }).then(balance => {
        setBalance(ethers.formatEther(balance));
    }).catch(console.error); // Add error handling
  }
}, [address]); // Re-run effect when address changes
```

